{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χᾰρά</b>, ἡ: <br /> (χαίρω):— <b>joy, delight,</b> first in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 1.6, then in Trag. and (less frequently) in Comedy texts and Prose: with _genitive_, στόματος ἐν πρώτῃ χ.,\">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>] of a hungry man, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Fragmenta - American Journal of Philology” 258 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; with <i>genitive</i> objecti, <b>joy in</b> or <b>at</b> a thing, μελέων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 579 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς χαρὰν λόγων in accordance with <b>joyous</b> tidings, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 179 (variant{χάριν})\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; κέρτομος θεοῦ χ. <b>a joy</b> sent by some mocking god, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Alcestis” 1125; ἅμα χαρᾷ δακρυούσας 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 7.2.9; χ. ἐπί τινι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Definitiones” 413e; ἔδωκας ἡμῖν χ. 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 201; ἐλάβομεν χ. 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Ion” 1449 (Lyric poetry); ἐμπλῆσαί τινα χαρᾶς [prev. author] “Ph.” 170; χαρά μ᾽ ὑφέρπει 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 270 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; λέγεις μοι χαράν wishest me <b>joy,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 637 (Lyric poetry); χ. ἐνεργάσασθαι 5th c.BC: Gorgias Rhetor et Sophista “Hel.” 8; χαίρειν ἀνδραπόδων τινὰ χαράν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.1091e, cf. NT.Matt.2.10; ἡδονὴ καὶ τέρψις καὶ χ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Philebus” 19; ἀπορέουσι.. χαρᾶς 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 293, compare 4th-3rd c.BC: Epicurus Philosophus “Fragmenta” 2; ζήλου καὶ χαρᾶς καὶ ἐπαίνων ἡ πόλις ἦν μεστή 4th c.BC: Demosthene